<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1922-03-11T03:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1922-03-11T03:00:00-05:00" n="664" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d664">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">493.11 Shelton, Dr. A. L.: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Schurman</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1922-03-11T16:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">March 11,
                                        1922—4 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received March 14—10:07
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>96. Legation’s 85, March 7, noon.<note n="28" xml:id="d664fn28">Not
                                printed.</note> On 10th I again addressed Foreign Office stating
                            receipt of confirmation of murder which now appeared indubitable. I
                            renewed request use every effort apprehend and try guilty parties
                            speediest possible manner, also requested in view of deep concern
                            American Government I receive earliest possible statement of steps taken
                            by Chinese Government.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Schurman</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>